=3D"text-align: center;"></td></tr></tbody></table></figure></div><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
>A reminder on how $UST works:</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">You can always redeem <strong>$L=
UNA</strong> for $UST dollar-for-dollar, and vice versa.</p><p style=3D"col=
or: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">If $LU=
NA is at $50, you can redeem it for 50 $UST.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a;=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Similarly, you can=
 redeem 50 $UST for 1 $LUNA.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">It's worth noting you can always r=
edeem 1 $UST for 1 dollar worth of $LUNA, even if $UST is worth &lt;$1.</p>=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 1em 0;">This part is confusing, but in English: <strong>&#8220;We promise =
to give you a dollar&#8217;s worth of something if you give us 1 $UST.&#822=
1; (that something, of course, being $LUNA).</strong></p><p style=3D"color:=
 #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">It's mean=
t to be a <strong>stabilizing mechanism</strong>:</p><p style=3D"color: #1a=
1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">If $UST is tr=
ading at $0.99, arbitrageurs can buy it and redeem it for $1 of $LUNA, pock=
eting $0.01. This is called the contraction phase, because demand for $UST =
is falling.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Of course when $UST is trading at $1.01, arbitrageu=
rs can do the inverse&#8211;trade $1 of $LUNA for 1 $UST, and pocket $0.01.=
 This is called the expansion phase, because demand for $UST is expanding. =
Note that another form of arbitrage also exists&#8211;simply selling 1 $UST=
 for $1.01 of $USDC.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">If you&#8217;re holding a dollar bill and =
someone says they&#8217;ll give you a dollar and a penny for it, you should=
 probably, uh, sell it.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">But of course curtailing expansion is e=
asier than fixing contraction. Why? When expansion (&#8220;too much demand&=
#8221;) occurs, $LUNA is burned for $UST, reducing $LUNA supply.</p><p styl=
e=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;=
">Assuming $LUNA demand stays fixed, $LUNA&#8217;s price goes up. Something=
 something economics 101. It&#8217;s the downside that&#8217;s important to=
 protect, and the way to do that is giving people a reason to hold $UST, or=
 some kind of utility.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>Stablecoins Require Utility</str=
ong>&#8482; to maintain demand and defend their peg.</p><p style=3D"color: =
#1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">So where d=
oes $UST get utility?</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Simple, <strong>Anchor Protocol</strong>.=
</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 1em 0;">Anchor Protocol is (nominally) a money market, but the importa=
nt tl;dr is it <strong>pays you 19.5% to stake $UST</strong>. You can think=
 of Anchor as a <strong>high-yield savings account</strong>.</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Af=
ter all, putting your money in a savings account is one way in which the US=
 dollar is useful. Of course it&#8217;s useful for many, many other things =
like buying groceries, paying taxes, and making origami swans.</p><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
